> Our beloved intern, Waad, wouldn't stop raving about his mother's famous stew recipe. After a little begging, we were lucky enough to get the original recipe sent all the way from Tunisia. A unique blend of nine spices gives this dish its character – we guarantee you've never tasted anything like it!

Preheat the oven to 400 degrees. Peel and finely dice the @carrots{6%ounce}(peeled and finely diced). Halve, peel, and finely dice the @yellow onion{1}(peeled and finely diced). Finely dice the @celery{1}(finely diced). Mince or grate the @garlic{2%cloves}(minced). Drain and rinse the @chickpeas{13.4%ounce}(drained and rinsed).

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{5%teaspoon} in a large #pot{} over medium heat. Add the onion, carrot, and celery and cook, tossing, for ~{7-8%minutes}, until softened and beginning to caramelize. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}. Add the garlic and 2 teaspoons @Tunisian Spice Blend{1%tablespoon} (we are sending 3) to the pot and cook for ~{1-2%minutes} more, until fragrant. Add ¼ cup @crushed tomatoes{13.76%ounce} to the pot and cook for another ~{1-2%minutes}. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Stir the @veggie stock concentrate{2} and @cracked freekeh{1/2%cup} and 4 cups water into the pot. Bring to a low simmer and cook for ~{20-25%minutes}, until the freekeh is tender. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

While the stew simmers, toss the chickpeas on a #baking sheet{} with the remaining Tunisian spice blend, 1 Tablespoon olive oil, and a pinch of salt and pepper. Place in the oven for ~{15-20%minutes}, until golden brown and crispy.

Finish and plate: Once the stew and chickpeas are ready, divide the stew between #bowls{}. Top each bowl with the crispy chickpeas, a dollop of @yogurt{5.3%ounce}, and a drizzle of olive oil. Enjoy!